1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,916
A prisoner. No lawyer.

2
00:00:01,916 --> 00:00:05,226
No law degree. A borrowed pencil and a

3
00:00:05,226 --> 00:00:08,448
few sheets of prison paper - about to

4
00:00:08,448 --> 00:00:12,106
beat the most powerful court in the world.

5
00:00:12,106 --> 00:00:14,022
Nine votes to nothing.

6
00:00:14,272 --> 00:00:17,233
In 1963, almost no one in America had

7
00:00:17,233 --> 00:00:20,115
heard the name Clarence Earl Gideon.

8
00:00:20,115 --> 00:00:22,596
He was a drifter, in and out of

9
00:00:22,596 --> 00:00:26,117
trouble his whole life, sitting in a Florida

10
00:00:26,117 --> 00:00:28,679
cell for a crime he swore he did

11
00:00:28,679 --> 00:00:31,800
not commit. He had stood in a courtroom

12
00:00:31,800 --> 00:00:35,002
and asked the judge for one simple thing

13
00:00:35,002 --> 00:00:37,403
- a lawyer. The judge said no.

14
00:00:37,403 --> 00:00:40,684
And that single word, "no," is where this

15
00:00:40,684 --> 00:00:42,445
story actually begins.

16
00:00:42,695 --> 00:00:45,489
Here is something most of us assume is

17
00:00:45,489 --> 00:00:48,284
just permanently true: that if you are

18
00:00:48,284 --> 00:00:51,666
arrested and cannot afford a lawyer, the court

19
00:00:51,666 --> 00:00:53,137
has to give you one.

20
00:00:53,137 --> 00:00:55,858
We treat it like a feature built into

21
00:00:55,858 --> 00:00:57,550
America from the start.

22
00:00:57,550 --> 00:01:00,344
It was not. For most of this country's

23
00:01:00,344 --> 00:01:03,065
history, if you were too poor to hire

24
00:01:03,065 --> 00:01:05,639
a lawyer, you could be put on trial

25
00:01:05,639 --> 00:01:08,507
alone - one frightened person against a

26
00:01:08,507 --> 00:01:11,595
trained prosecutor whose entire job was to

27
00:01:11,595 --> 00:01:14,757
convict you. The guarantee of a free lawyer

28
00:01:14,757 --> 00:01:17,258
is younger than your grandparents.

29
00:01:17,258 --> 00:01:19,978
And it exists because of one stubborn

30
00:01:19,978 --> 00:01:22,994
prisoner, one handwritten letter, and one

31
00:01:22,994 --> 00:01:24,979
unanimous decision in 1963.

32
00:01:24,979 --> 00:01:27,847
Over the next twelve minutes: how a man

33
00:01:27,847 --> 00:01:31,230
nobody believed in forced the Supreme Court to

34
00:01:31,230 --> 00:01:34,465
rewrite the rules of every criminal trial in

35
00:01:34,465 --> 00:01:37,848
America - and the imperfect system that ruling

36
00:01:37,848 --> 00:01:38,731
left behind.

37
00:01:38,981 --> 00:01:41,715
Start in a Florida courtroom, 1961.

38
00:01:41,715 --> 00:01:45,230
Clarence Earl Gideon is charged with breaking

39
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:48,589
into a poolroom and stealing a little money

40
00:01:48,589 --> 00:01:51,792
and some bottles of drink - under Florida

41
00:01:51,792 --> 00:01:53,823
law, a felony. He is poor.

42
00:01:53,823 --> 00:01:56,323
He has been in and out of prison

43
00:01:56,323 --> 00:01:59,292
before. And he knows, the way you know

44
00:01:59,292 --> 00:02:02,026
a thing in your gut, that he cannot

45
00:02:02,026 --> 00:02:03,120
do this alone.

46
00:02:03,370 --> 00:02:05,853
So he asks the court to appoint a

47
00:02:05,853 --> 00:02:08,789
lawyer for him. The judge tells him the

48
00:02:08,789 --> 00:02:11,348
law does not allow it - in Florida

49
00:02:11,348 --> 00:02:14,358
at that time, a free lawyer was provided

50
00:02:14,358 --> 00:02:17,068
only when a person's life was on the

51
00:02:17,068 --> 00:02:19,326
line, in a death-penalty case.

52
00:02:19,326 --> 00:02:21,885
Gideon's case is not one of those.

53
00:02:21,885 --> 00:02:25,121
The chair where his lawyer should sit stays

54
00:02:25,121 --> 00:02:25,573
empty.

55
00:02:25,823 --> 00:02:28,478
Picture what a trial actually is.

56
00:02:28,478 --> 00:02:31,215
It is a contest with rules - rules

57
00:02:31,215 --> 00:02:34,272
about what evidence can come in, which

58
00:02:34,272 --> 00:02:37,330
questions can be asked, what a jury is

59
00:02:37,330 --> 00:02:40,308
allowed to hear. On one side stands a

60
00:02:40,308 --> 00:02:43,527
prosecutor who has done this hundreds of

61
00:02:43,527 --> 00:02:46,826
times, who knows every one of those rules

62
00:02:46,826 --> 00:02:50,045
by heart. On the other side, now, stands

63
00:02:50,045 --> 00:02:53,747
Gideon: no training, no preparation, trying to

64
00:02:53,747 --> 00:02:56,885
defend his own freedom in a language he

65
00:02:56,885 --> 00:02:58,092
does not speak.

66
00:02:58,342 --> 00:03:00,945
He does his best. He makes an opening

67
00:03:00,945 --> 00:03:04,040
statement, he questions witnesses, he argues

68
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:06,502
to the jury. But doing your best is

69
00:03:06,502 --> 00:03:09,034
not the same as knowing what you are

70
00:03:09,034 --> 00:03:12,199
doing. The verdict comes back guilty, and the

71
00:03:12,199 --> 00:03:15,083
court sends him to prison for five years.

72
00:03:15,333 --> 00:03:18,385
For almost anyone else, that is the end.

73
00:03:18,385 --> 00:03:21,590
A poor man, convicted, locked away, out of

74
00:03:21,590 --> 00:03:24,642
moves. But Gideon has one move left that

75
00:03:24,642 --> 00:03:27,236
no one expects - and it costs five

76
00:03:27,236 --> 00:03:27,694
cents.

77
00:03:27,944 --> 00:03:30,899
In his cell, Gideon does something quietly

78
00:03:30,899 --> 00:03:33,924
extraordinary. He gets hold of a pencil and

79
00:03:33,924 --> 00:03:36,315
some prison paper, and in careful,

80
00:03:36,315 --> 00:03:39,551
hand-printed letters he writes directly to the

81
00:03:39,551 --> 00:03:42,576
Supreme Court of the United States - asking

82
00:03:42,576 --> 00:03:44,124
them to hear his case.

83
00:03:44,374 --> 00:03:47,402
He cannot pay the court's fees, so he

84
00:03:47,402 --> 00:03:50,348
files as what the law calls a pauper

85
00:03:50,348 --> 00:03:52,557
- a person too poor to pay.

86
00:03:52,557 --> 00:03:54,357
No firm is behind him.

87
00:03:54,357 --> 00:03:57,221
No famous attorney is making calls.

88
00:03:57,221 --> 00:04:00,658
It is just one prisoner, arguing that what

89
00:04:00,658 --> 00:04:03,849
happened to him - being tried without a

90
00:04:03,849 --> 00:04:06,631
lawyer - was not just unlucky, but

91
00:04:06,631 --> 00:04:08,022
unconstitutional.

92
00:04:08,272 --> 00:04:11,413
And here is the wall standing directly in

93
00:04:11,413 --> 00:04:14,477
his way. Twenty years earlier, in a case

94
00:04:14,477 --> 00:04:17,847
called Betts v. Brady, the Supreme Court had

95
00:04:17,847 --> 00:04:21,371
already looked at almost this exact question -

96
00:04:21,371 --> 00:04:23,515
and had ruled the other way.

97
00:04:23,515 --> 00:04:26,426
Betts said that states did not have to

98
00:04:26,426 --> 00:04:29,107
hand every poor defendant a lawyer.

99
00:04:29,107 --> 00:04:32,401
A free lawyer was required only in "special

100
00:04:32,401 --> 00:04:35,694
circumstances" - if you were very young, or

101
00:04:35,694 --> 00:04:38,835
could not read, or the case was unusually

102
00:04:38,835 --> 00:04:42,282
complex. An ordinary poor man, in an ordinary

103
00:04:42,282 --> 00:04:45,346
case, was expected to manage on his own.

104
00:04:45,596 --> 00:04:48,267
So Gideon is not just asking the Court

105
00:04:48,267 --> 00:04:50,658
to help him. He is asking the most

106
00:04:50,658 --> 00:04:53,540
powerful court in the country to admit it

107
00:04:53,540 --> 00:04:56,072
had been wrong - to overturn its own

108
00:04:56,072 --> 00:04:59,236
decision and rewrite the rule for every state

109
00:04:59,236 --> 00:05:02,118
at once. Prisoners send the Supreme Court

110
00:05:02,118 --> 00:05:05,352
thousands of these handwritten petitions every

111
00:05:05,352 --> 00:05:08,165
year. The Court turns away almost all of

112
00:05:08,165 --> 00:05:08,516
them.

113
00:05:08,766 --> 00:05:10,865
It did not turn away Gideon's.

114
00:05:10,865 --> 00:05:13,524
The justices agreed to hear the case -

115
00:05:13,524 --> 00:05:16,532
and then did something that turns the whole

116
00:05:16,532 --> 00:05:17,791
story on its head.

117
00:05:17,791 --> 00:05:20,310
The man who had been denied a lawyer

118
00:05:20,310 --> 00:05:22,759
in Florida was now given one of the

119
00:05:22,759 --> 00:05:25,977
finest lawyers in America: the Court appointed

120
00:05:25,977 --> 00:05:29,055
a top Washington attorney named Abe Fortas -

121
00:05:29,055 --> 00:05:32,064
a future Supreme Court justice himself - to

122
00:05:32,064 --> 00:05:33,463
argue Gideon's side.

123
00:05:33,713 --> 00:05:36,667
The question was no longer just about one

124
00:05:36,667 --> 00:05:38,973
man in one cell. It had become a

125
00:05:38,973 --> 00:05:42,000
question about every poor defendant in the

126
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,170
country. Did the Constitution promise them a

127
00:05:45,170 --> 00:05:46,684
lawyer, or didn't it?

128
00:05:46,934 --> 00:05:50,405
On March 18, 1963, the Supreme Court answered

129
00:05:50,405 --> 00:05:53,028
- and this time the answer was not

130
00:05:53,028 --> 00:05:55,652
close. The decision was unanimous.

131
00:05:55,652 --> 00:05:57,812
Every single justice agreed.

132
00:05:57,812 --> 00:06:01,052
Justice Hugo Black, writing for the Court,

133
00:06:01,052 --> 00:06:02,672
delivered the ruling.

134
00:06:02,922 --> 00:06:06,376
The reasoning was almost startlingly plain.

135
00:06:06,376 --> 00:06:10,071
The Sixth Amendment promises anyone accused of

136
00:06:10,071 --> 00:06:13,364
a crime "the assistance of counsel" - the

137
00:06:13,364 --> 00:06:16,335
help of a lawyer. The Court said that

138
00:06:16,335 --> 00:06:19,468
promise is not a luxury or a formality.

139
00:06:19,468 --> 00:06:22,761
In our system, where the government hires

140
00:06:22,761 --> 00:06:26,455
trained prosecutors and builds courthouses and

141
00:06:26,455 --> 00:06:29,748
writes the rules of evidence, a lawyer is

142
00:06:29,748 --> 00:06:32,640
not a frill. A lawyer is a necessity

143
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:35,692
- without one, the trial itself is not

144
00:06:35,692 --> 00:06:36,575
truly fair.

145
00:06:36,825 --> 00:06:39,361
And because a fair trial is a basic

146
00:06:39,361 --> 00:06:42,621
right, the Court held, that right cannot stop

147
00:06:42,621 --> 00:06:44,866
at the federal courthouse door.

148
00:06:44,866 --> 00:06:48,198
Through the Fourteenth Amendment, it binds the

149
00:06:48,198 --> 00:06:51,386
states too. From that day forward, any state

150
00:06:51,386 --> 00:06:53,994
putting a poor person on trial for a

151
00:06:53,994 --> 00:06:56,819
serious crime had to give that person a

152
00:06:56,819 --> 00:06:59,499
lawyer - and if they could not afford

153
00:06:59,499 --> 00:07:01,962
one, the state had to provide one.

154
00:07:02,212 --> 00:07:04,638
To say all of this, the Court had

155
00:07:04,638 --> 00:07:07,210
to do the thing Gideon had dared to

156
00:07:07,210 --> 00:07:10,297
ask for. It reached back and overruled its

157
00:07:10,297 --> 00:07:11,987
own precedent. Betts v.

158
00:07:11,987 --> 00:07:14,633
Brady - the wall - was knocked down.

159
00:07:14,633 --> 00:07:18,014
The old "special circumstances" test was gone.

160
00:07:18,014 --> 00:07:21,028
The new rule was simple enough for anyone

161
00:07:21,028 --> 00:07:23,747
to understand: if you are too poor to

162
00:07:23,747 --> 00:07:26,760
hire a lawyer, the state must appoint one

163
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:27,348
for you.

164
00:07:27,598 --> 00:07:30,462
A handwritten letter from a prison cell had

165
00:07:30,462 --> 00:07:33,525
just rewritten the law for the entire country.

166
00:07:33,525 --> 00:07:35,590
But it had not yet done the one

167
00:07:35,590 --> 00:07:37,588
thing Gideon cared about most.

168
00:07:37,838 --> 00:07:41,191
Because winning at the Supreme Court did not

169
00:07:41,191 --> 00:07:44,696
set Gideon free. It did something narrower: it

170
00:07:44,696 --> 00:07:47,896
threw out his conviction and sent him back

171
00:07:47,896 --> 00:07:50,411
to Florida for a brand-new trial.

172
00:07:50,411 --> 00:07:52,850
The same charges. The same town.

173
00:07:52,850 --> 00:07:56,050
But this time, the empty chair was filled.

174
00:07:56,050 --> 00:07:59,403
Gideon walked into that second trial with an

175
00:07:59,403 --> 00:08:01,537
appointed lawyer beside him.

176
00:08:01,787 --> 00:08:04,460
And the difference was night and day.

177
00:08:04,460 --> 00:08:07,711
A real defense attorney picked the case apart

178
00:08:07,711 --> 00:08:11,034
- testing the witnesses, poking at the state's

179
00:08:11,034 --> 00:08:14,212
story, doing all the things Gideon had never

180
00:08:14,212 --> 00:08:15,802
known how to do alone.

181
00:08:15,802 --> 00:08:18,402
This time, the jury came back with a

182
00:08:18,402 --> 00:08:20,353
different word: not guilty.

183
00:08:20,603 --> 00:08:23,339
Sit with that contrast for a second.

184
00:08:23,339 --> 00:08:26,304
The very same man, facing the very same

185
00:08:26,304 --> 00:08:29,649
accusation. Alone, he was convicted and sent

186
00:08:29,649 --> 00:08:32,842
to prison. With a lawyer, he was acquitted

187
00:08:32,842 --> 00:08:34,362
and walked out free.

188
00:08:34,362 --> 00:08:36,870
Nothing about Gideon had changed.

189
00:08:36,870 --> 00:08:40,367
The only thing that changed was whether anyone

190
00:08:40,367 --> 00:08:43,256
in that room was standing on his side.

191
00:08:43,256 --> 00:08:46,373
That gap - between facing the state alone

192
00:08:46,373 --> 00:08:48,805
and facing it with help - is the

193
00:08:48,805 --> 00:08:51,162
entire reason the right exists.

194
00:08:51,412 --> 00:08:54,265
And Gideon's win did not stay with Gideon.

195
00:08:54,265 --> 00:08:57,050
His name became the key that unlocked the

196
00:08:57,050 --> 00:08:59,428
same right for everyone behind him.

197
00:08:59,428 --> 00:09:02,078
Across the country, states had to build

198
00:09:02,078 --> 00:09:04,999
something new to keep the promise the Court

199
00:09:04,999 --> 00:09:07,988
had just made: offices full of lawyers whose

200
00:09:07,988 --> 00:09:10,570
job is to defend people who cannot pay

201
00:09:10,570 --> 00:09:12,132
- the public defenders.

202
00:09:12,132 --> 00:09:14,578
If you have ever heard the phrase "a

203
00:09:14,578 --> 00:09:17,703
public defender will be assigned to you," that

204
00:09:17,703 --> 00:09:20,353
system traces back, in large part, to a

205
00:09:20,353 --> 00:09:21,575
prisoner's pencil.

206
00:09:21,825 --> 00:09:24,741
But this is where the hidden room opens

207
00:09:24,741 --> 00:09:27,059
- and it is not a tidy victory.

208
00:09:27,059 --> 00:09:29,975
The Court could create the right with a

209
00:09:29,975 --> 00:09:31,320
stroke of the pen.

210
00:09:31,320 --> 00:09:34,087
It could not, with that same pen, pay

211
00:09:34,087 --> 00:09:36,329
for it. A right to a lawyer is

212
00:09:36,329 --> 00:09:39,245
only as real as the lawyer you actually

213
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:42,011
get. And in the decades since, public

214
00:09:42,011 --> 00:09:45,226
defenders have often been buried - too many

215
00:09:45,226 --> 00:09:48,665
clients, too little money, too little time for

216
00:09:48,665 --> 00:09:52,104
each case. The promise is guaranteed on paper.

217
00:09:52,104 --> 00:09:55,020
Whether it is fully kept, case by case,

218
00:09:55,020 --> 00:09:58,459
still depends on resources no court can simply

219
00:09:58,459 --> 00:09:59,730
order into being.

220
00:09:59,980 --> 00:10:03,200
So Gideon answered the question Miranda would

221
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:04,918
raise three years later.

222
00:10:04,918 --> 00:10:07,637
When a suspect is told, "if you cannot

223
00:10:07,637 --> 00:10:10,643
afford a lawyer, one will be appointed for

224
00:10:10,643 --> 00:10:13,290
you," those words are not a courtesy.

225
00:10:13,290 --> 00:10:15,437
They are a promise - and it is

226
00:10:15,437 --> 00:10:16,654
Gideon's promise.

227
00:10:16,904 --> 00:10:19,356
Step back, and the shape of it is

228
00:10:19,356 --> 00:10:21,065
almost hard to believe.

229
00:10:21,065 --> 00:10:23,221
We did not get the right to a

230
00:10:23,221 --> 00:10:25,970
free lawyer from a great speech, or a

231
00:10:25,970 --> 00:10:29,017
famous senator, or a crowd in the street.

232
00:10:29,017 --> 00:10:32,064
We got it because one poor, twice-doubted

233
00:10:32,064 --> 00:10:35,260
prisoner refused to accept that justice was

234
00:10:35,260 --> 00:10:38,529
something only people with money could buy -

235
00:10:38,529 --> 00:10:41,428
and because he wrote it down and mailed

236
00:10:41,428 --> 00:10:41,874
it in.

237
00:10:42,124 --> 00:10:45,368
Clarence Earl Gideon got the ending you almost

238
00:10:45,368 --> 00:10:48,048
never get. He won at the highest court

239
00:10:48,048 --> 00:10:50,304
in the land, and then he won his

240
00:10:50,304 --> 00:10:53,125
freedom too. But the thing he really won

241
00:10:53,125 --> 00:10:54,747
was never just for him.

242
00:10:54,747 --> 00:10:56,581
He won a rule - that in an

243
00:10:56,581 --> 00:10:59,614
American courtroom, you do not have to face

244
00:10:59,614 --> 00:11:02,153
the full weight of the state with an

245
00:11:02,153 --> 00:11:03,775
empty chair beside you.

246
00:11:04,025 --> 00:11:07,329
That is the hidden system behind a phrase

247
00:11:07,329 --> 00:11:09,828
you have heard a hundred times.

248
00:11:09,828 --> 00:11:12,891
"You have the right to an attorney" is

249
00:11:12,891 --> 00:11:15,953
not set dressing. It is a promise paid

250
00:11:15,953 --> 00:11:18,613
for by a prisoner with a pencil -

251
00:11:18,613 --> 00:11:21,756
powerful, real, and still, to this day,

252
00:11:21,756 --> 00:11:25,142
unfinished. Next time, we open the door on

253
00:11:25,142 --> 00:11:28,124
who decides what counts as a crime in

254
00:11:28,124 --> 00:11:31,428
the first place. Until then: now you know

255
00:11:31,428 --> 00:11:34,411
who actually gets a lawyer - and why.
